Here is a script for you to update `persistent_peers` setting in `config.toml`. Stale peers can cause node inefficiency over time, so the script below selects a few random live peers.

```bash
PEERS=3b9c10cb2eb977e1707c73734eb3e11fdee5e6d9@65.109.123.185:20556,09b1a88148c16a3cc629b7cfc12fb369d7a3399a@65.108.233.90:20056,176107e1a0f283a63c3a06025f073cb3711c9931@148.251.6.248:20556,a3ee63fb71b864ec86df0f0fec78aa2b587330c1@37.27.59.58:26656,9af51e7767db015da4001681cb7d2262ab46440a@65.108.44.241:1520
sed -i.bak -e "s/^persistent_peers *=.*/persistent_peers = \"$PEERS\"/" ~/.dymension/config/config.toml

sudo systemctl restart dymd
sudo journalctl -fu dymd --no-hostname -o cat
```
